</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D6540FF98BD14FAE3F933F60FF97F" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BB836CBFF98BD14FAE3F933F60FF97F" blockId="4.[1378,2585,1164,2064]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis id="B973EAD9FF98BD14FAE3F933F7BEF907" bold="true" box="[1380,2085,1676,1709]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
The Qinling Zokor prefers to construct burrows in soft soils with few rocks on sunny slopes with sparse shrubs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D6540FF98BD14FAE3F964F84FF8D8" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8BB836CBFF98BD14FAE3F964F84FF8D8" blockId="4.[1378,2585,1164,2064]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis id="B973EAD9FF98BD14FAE3F964F925F956" bold="true" box="[1380,1726,1755,1788]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Not assessed on The IUCN Red List. Classified as data deficient on the 2016 China Red List, where it is treated as a distinct species. The Qinling Zokor seems to benefit from an intermediate level of human disturbance such as cleared land near highways. It is an agricultural pest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D6540FF98BD14FAE3F83EF6C9F7BA" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="bibRefCitation_list">
<paragraph id="8BB836CBFF98BD14FAE3F83EF6C9F7BA" blockId="4.[1378,2585,1164,2064]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
